article.description:
Janell Burse scored 23 points and Betty Lennox
had 18 of her 22 in the first half as the Seattle Storm defeated
the Charlotte Sting 87-81 Saturday night.
article.headline: Storm win to stay just ahead of rising Mercury
article.linkText: Storm win to stay just ahead of rising Mercury
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Coming off a roller-coaster 10-day stretch, Betty
Lennox wanted to get off to a strong start.

Lennox scored 18 of her 22 points in the first half to lead the
Seattle Storm to an 87-81 victory over the Charlotte Sting on
Saturday night.

Lennox shot a two-pointer instead of a 3 as time expired in a
recent one-point home loss to Los Angeles, then hit the
game-winning 3-- her only field goal -- at Minnesota, and managed
just four points in Thursday's home win over Washington.

"I really just tried to look past my leg," said Lennox, wh��r-14 shooting. Kelly Mazzante and Tangela Smith each
had 16 points for the Sting, who are 0-6 in Seattle.

Jackson had back-to-back layups, after going 18 minutes without
a field goal, to give the Storm a 51-43 lead in the third.

After Charlotte pulled to 63-60, Sue Bird's jumper -- her first
field goal of the game due to Helen Darling's constant pressure --
gave Seattle a 70-62 lead and the Sting never recovered. Charlotte
trailed by as many as 13 points.

"In that fourth quarter, we finally had a surge," said Seattle
coach Anne Donovan, who won her 120th game as a WNBA coach to pass
Michael Cooper for third all-time.

The Storm shot 49 percent and outrebounded the Sting 41-25 to
overcome 24 turnovers. Seattle, with 30 made free throws, almost
doubled the Sting's attempts -- 16.

"We didn't get any calls to go our way, it was very lopsided,"
Bogues said.

Chrlotte, the second-worst shooting team in the WNBA, shot 38
percent and had 22 more field-goal attempts than Seattle.

Seattle controlled the first half before Charlotte moved ahead
34-33 after getting eight points from Mazzante on three consecutive
possessions. It was the Sting's first lead since 4-2.

"In the early stages, their post players really had their way
against us, and after that their shooters had their way," Donovan
said. "And then from there we cleaned it up defensively."

Burse had two straight field goals to give Seattle the lead for
good at 37-34. The Storm led 45-43 at halftime.

Tammy Sutton-Brown, the second-leading shot blocker in the
league, was out with back spasms suffered in Charlotte's 112-84
loss to Phoenix on Thursday. Rookie Tye'sha Fluker made her first
start in Sutton-Brown's place and had two points.
